Part 1

The oxygen cylinder beside the bed had a small brass regulator that leaked. If you stood near the head of the bed, in the quiet spaces between the household noises, you could hear it clearly—a tiny, dry hiss like steam escaping a pipe three rooms away. 

Vikram had tried to tighten it twice with a spanner he had borrowed from the driver. Both times, the sound had stopped for ten minutes, then returned, slightly thinner but completely unchanged.

Binay Ahuja didn't seem to mind the sound. Or perhaps he had simply stopped separating the mechanical noise of the room from the sound of his own shallow breathing. 

His skin had gone the grey-yellow color of an old newspaper left out in the rain.

"Rohan didn't come today," Binay said, his eyes remaining closed. His voice was barely louder than the regulator's hiss.

"He had site inspections at the Nandyal plant, Papa," Vikram said.

"A construction site doesn't go anywhere, Vikram."

"There was a concrete mixing ratio issue. He wanted to check the quality himself."

Binay closed his eyes tighter. The saline line taped to his forearm was empty, and a single bubble of air was trapped near the plastic lock, refusing to move up or down the tube.

"He thinks I don't know," Binay whispered, his lips dry.

"Know what, Papa?"

"That he took that engineering job because he didn't want to sit in your shadow here in Calcutta."

Vikram didn't answer. He sat on the folding metal chair near the wardrobe, his hands clasped between his knees. 

The bedroom smelled of boiled barley water, old dust, and the rubbing spirit the nurse used to clean the thermometer.

"Let him," Binay said, after a long silence. "It is better to build a small wall yourself than to live in a palace someone else gave you."

---

The phone call came at four in the morning. It was the family doctor, Dr. Joshi, calling from the house. 

He didn't use the words he usually used during his weekly checks. There was no talk of *portal pressure* or *we'll monitor the vitals.* 

He simply said: "Vikram. Come."

---

The family house in Odisha had two gates. 

The main gate was wide, iron-grilled, with two granite pillars that had *Ahuja Villa* engraved in white marble plates. The side gate was small, painted green, leading directly through a gap in the boundary wall to the kitchen garden.

Vikram used the side gate when the car pulled up. 

The kitchen was already open, the lights bright. The old family cook, Ramu, was sitting on a low wooden stool, cleaning cardamom pods in a wide brass plate. 

He didn't look up when Vikram entered, his fingers moving slowly. "Joshi saab is inside," Ramu said, sorting the black seeds from the green husks. "He asked for black coffee."

"Is Rohan here?"

"He arrived at three. He is in the study room."

Vikram walked down the long corridor. The house felt larger than it had yesterday, the high ceilings echoing the silence. 

The lights were all turned on, but they seemed to illuminate only the corners of the rooms, leaving the heavy teak furniture in a grey, unmoving shade.

Dr. Joshi was standing near the study door, his stethoscope already packed, his black leather bag zipped and placed on the corner table. He looked at Vikram and nodded once.

"Heart stopped at three-forty," the doctor said, his voice quiet. "No pain. He simply ceased."

Vikram stood there, his eyes fixed on the doctor's bag. It was a black leather bag with a worn handle, the leather peeling near the brass lock to show the grey fabric underneath.

"Rohan is inside," Joshi said, touching Vikram's arm briefly as he walked toward the door. "Go talk to him."

---

The study room was cold. Binay's large teak wood desk was completely empty, except for a brass paperweight shaped like a lion.

Rohan was sitting in the guest chair. His leather shoes were covered in red Nandyal dust, a dry crust of it clinging to the welt of his left heel.

He didn't look up when Vikram entered the room. "You should have called me earlier," Rohan said, his voice flat.

"I called at midnight, Rohan. Your phone was switched off."

"The site office has no network after ten. You know that."

"I sent the driver to fetch you."

"The driver took three hours to reach the site," Rohan said. His voice was tight and thin, like a wire drawn too straight. "He arrived after the doctor had already signed the death certificate."

He stood up and walked to the window, looking out at the dark kitchen garden where Ramu was now throwing kitchen waste into the compost pit.

"Rohan," Vikram said.

"Don't," Rohan said, his back still turned. "Don't use that tone. The 'elder brother' tone."

He turned back to face the room. His lip was still slightly dark near the corner where the contractor's men had hit him three months ago.

"Everyone at the construction site knew before I did," Rohan said, his eyes narrowing. "The contractor's supervisor came to my cabin at two. He said, 'Ahuja Sahib is serious, you should leave.' He said it like he was giving me a concession."

"He was trying to help, Rohan."

"He was showing me that even my father's death is company business," Rohan said. He walked to the desk, his finger tracing the brass lion's mane. 

"Seven hundred crore. Fourteen hundred crore. Ten thousand crore. That's what you and Reddy talk about in the office. That's what is printed in the financial papers."

He looked at Vikram properly now. "Papa died in this house. The house belongs to the company. The car Dr. Joshi came in belongs to the company. Even the shroud we will buy today will be billed to the office account."

"Rohan—"

"I don't want it," Rohan said. He spoke louder now, his voice echoing off the high ceiling of the study. "I don't want your charity. I don't want to be the younger brother who was given a site-engineer job to keep him quiet."

"You chose that job yourself."

"Because it was the only one where nobody asked who my brother was!"

A heavy silence followed. The old ceiling fan in the study gave a low, metallic groan as it turned.

Rohan sat back down in the guest chair. "He wanted a doctor," Rohan whispered, looking at the empty desk. "He wanted you to wear the white coat. He told me that when I was twelve. 'Vicky will be the doctor.' He said it like I was just the spare."

"He didn't mean that, Rohan."

"He did," Rohan said. "And then you left the college. You took the office. You took the board. You took the South expansion. You took everything he had to give." He looked at his hands, at the red dust under his nails. "And now he is gone."

---

Vikram didn't go to the city office the next day, or the week after that. He stayed in the house, sitting in the small room off the kitchen.

Reddy came twice. Sinha came once. They sat in the drawing room, drank the tea Ramu brought, and talked about the transition of power.

"We need signatures, Vikram," Reddy said during the second visit. "The Nandyal plant phase two needs approval. The banks are waiting."

"Ask Rohan to sign," Vikram said.

Reddy laughed, a short, dry sound. "Rohan? He is an engineer, Vikram. The board won't accept his signature on a financial release."

"They will," Vikram said. "If he owns the shares."

Reddy stopped laughing, his eyes narrowing. "What are you saying?"

"Prepare the transfer documents," Vikram said. "The shares, the house, the Odisha license. Everything Binay Ahuja left behind. Transfer it all to Rohan."

"You are out of your mind," Reddy said, standing up. "He cannot run this. He doesn't know the distributors. He doesn't know the MLA."

"He will learn," Vikram said. "I learned."

---

The lawyer brought the transfer papers on Friday afternoon. The study room was hot, and Ramu had forgotten to turn on the cooler.

Rohan stood near the desk, but he didn't touch the pen. "Why are you doing this, Vikram?"

"Because you want it," Vikram said.

"I didn't ask for a gift."

"It's not a gift," Vikram said. "It is what is yours."

He picked up the pen and signed first. His signature had become neat over the ten years, the letters even, the 'A' sharp and clear. He set the pen down.

"The driver is waiting outside," Vikram said. "The keys to the city office are on the table."

Rohan looked at the signed papers. His hand trembled slightly as he picked up the pen to sign below Vikram's name. He didn't look at his brother.

"Where will you go?" Rohan asked, his voice low.

"Sarita's place," Vikram said. "Near the bypass."

Rohan's pen stopped. "The AIDS shelter?"

"Yes."

"People will talk, Vikram. They will say I pushed you out."

"Let them," Vikram said. "They have been talking since 1995. It is their business."

He picked up his small leather bag from the floor. It contained two shirts, one pair of trousers, and nothing else. 

He walked out of the study. He didn't use the main gate. 

He walked through the kitchen, passed Ramu who was still sorting cardamoms, and went out of the green side gate.

The road outside was dusty, and the afternoon sun was direct and sharp. He didn't call a cab. He walked toward the bypass, his bag in his left hand, his face toward the heat.

[End of Part 1]
